{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1097"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1097"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.7,0.14,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1097"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of worsening bloody diarrhoea, abdominal pain, and fatigue. He reports passing more than six bloody stools per day. He has a six-month history of intermittent diarrhoea and has lost 5 kg unintentionally during this period. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 120/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He has pale conjunctivae and a soft, non-distended abdomen with moderate tenderness in the lower quadrants bilaterally. Amongst various investigations, a colonoscopy is arranged. A view of the descending colon is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Angioembolisation","Intravenous corticosteroids","Intravenous ceftriaxone and metronidazole","Surgical resection","Endoscopic clipping"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with findings suggestive of acute severe ulcerative colitis (UC). The colonoscopy shows inflammatory changes of ulcerative colitis including ulceration, friability and decreased vascular markings. The most appropriate next step in management is administration of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E. IV corticosteroids are the first-line treatment for severe UC and act rapidly to reduce inflammation and control symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E are antibiotics that may be used in certain gastrointestinal infections such as diverticulitis. However, they are not the primary treatment for a severe UC flare and would not be the most appropriate next step in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical resection\u003C/strong\u003E is a last resort for severe UC that is refractory to medical management or in cases of toxic megacolon or perforation. It would not be the next step in this acute presentation without first attempting medical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic clipping \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eangioembolisation\u003C/strong\u003E are methods of controlling gastrointestinal bleeding. CT angiography with embolisation is particularly useful in cases of unstable gastrointestinal bleeding or when a bleeding lesion cannot be readily identified or treated endoscopically. These are not usually required or appropriate in UC, where bleeding is generally managed through treatment of inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous corticosteroids are the first-line treatment for severe ulcerative colitis.","Ulcerative colitis is characterized by continuous, diffuse mucosal inflammation which spreads retrograde beginning at the rectum.","Endoscopic findings of ulcerative colitis include ulceration, friability and loss of vascular markings"],"references":["Walk A. Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of irritable bowel syndrome in adults. In: UpToDate [online]. 2021 [cited 11 July 2021]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-irritable-bowel-syndrome-in-adults","Pemberton J. Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of acute colonic diverticulitis in adults. In: UpToDate [online]. 2021 [cited 11 July 2021]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-acute-diverticulitis-in-adults?search=diverticulitis%20diagnosis\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","Australian Guidelines for General Practitioners and Physicians: Inflammatory Bowel Disease 4th Edition. In GESA [online]. 2018 [cited 11 July 2021]. Available at: https://www.gesa.org.au/public/13/files/Education%20%26%20Resources/Clinical%20Practice%20Resources/IBD/2018_IBD_Clinical_Update_May_update.pdf","Macrae F, Parikh A. Clinical presentation, diagnosis and staging of colorectal cancer. In: UpToDate [online]. 2021 [cited 11 Jul 2021]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-presentation-diagnosis-and-staging-of-colorectal-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1097"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16862"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16862"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ae66b8d3-dbda-41a2-a796-1851d6d7c5bb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ae66b8d3-dbda-41a2-a796-1851d6d7c5bb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":297,"height":286}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T20:52:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T11:39:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1097"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55947"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their